<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920212-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>920212-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief -- Collagen Corp.:   Firm Says Judge Dismissed   Lawsuit Over Its Implants</HL><DATE>02/12/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   CGEN</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>BIOTECHNOLOGY (BTC)MEDICAL andamp; BIOTECHNOLOGY, GENETIC RESEARCH, PROSTHETICS (MTC)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Collagen Corp. said a judge granted its request to dismissa lawsuit filed by a woman who claimed that collagen implantscaused her to develop a rare disease.   The company, based in Palo Alto, Calif., said Judge DavidMazzone of the U.S. District Court for Massachusettsdismissed the lawsuit. The suit claimed that the company wasnegligent in the testing, manufacture and sale of injectablecollagen implants, which can be used in various parts of thebody. The plantiff claimed that use of the implants causedher to develop an autoimmune disease.</LP><TEXT>   Over the last decade, Collagen has been sued by 14 peoplewho claimed they developed autoimmune diseases after usingthe company's products. The company said 13 of those caseshave been resolved in its favor, and one was settled inconjunction with its insurance company.</TEXT></DOC>